ompetitor economies.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.44pt; padding-bottom:10pt; padding-left:6.56pt; padding-right:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">Local areas outside London, particularly in the North</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> have received a disproportionately low level of funding in a number of areas, such as major transport infrastructure an</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">d arts funding</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> – for example in 20122/12, £656 per capita was spent on transport in London, against £236 per capita in the north</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">(S</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">ource: IPPR</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.44pt; padding-bottom:10pt; padding-left:6.56pt; padding-right:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">The relationship between central and local government should be formalised by statute. To this end, a Royal Commission should be set in train, similar to the Calman Review for Scotland or the Silk Review for Wales, to cover responsibilities, funding (inclu</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">ding taxation) and the constitutional relationship between Whitehall and local authorities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.44pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:6.56pt; padding-right:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">Restrictions on the ability to raise levies for economic growth and council tax should be amended or lifted. Local authorities should have greater powers to set and</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> retain business rates for their area.</span></li></ul></div><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Background </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">City of York Council </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">York is a medium-sized city, with a population of just under 200,000, but has benefited from its position as a major centre for tourism, as well as being a centre for education with t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">wo universities, and has </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">recently </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">successfully tr</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">ansitioned from a manufacturing</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> economy to a service- and knowledge economy. In terms of business rates, it is a net contributor to the pool, and is planning to bring new commercial developments on-stream ov</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">er the next five years.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">The City of York Council is doing everything it can with the powers available to support the development of the city. We have taken advantage of the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">recently-grante</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">d powers under the Localism Act</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> Examples of this include: </span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 47.44pt; padding-left:6.56pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">With the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> removal of some of the restrictions on trading, City of York Council has set up its own local authority trading company (LATC), which enables a range of service</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">s to be offered externally including recruitment. We have also recently set up a new company th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">at will manage the promotion of city </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">to visitors and investors. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 47.44pt; padding-left:6.56pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">While York has excellent transport links</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> both regionally and nationally,  w</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">e are working across </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">West Yorkshire</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> to ensure York has the transport capacity to support long term growth It is impo</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">rtant that York has the right transport infrastructure for future, this includes ensuring adequate public transport across our travel to work area (which includes cities in the ne</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">ighbouring area, such as Leeds)</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">. </span></li></ul></ol><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Main points</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">The current piecemeal approach to funding </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">across the country</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">, divided by Whitehall department, has not proved an efficient way of managing resources. At a local level, much effort goes into managing a number of competing and overlapping bids for funding</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">The concentration of investment in London is detrimental in effect to the capital as well as to the regions, as house prices and transport costs continue to rise well above the rate of wages, to the point where workers can neither afford to live in London </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">or travel to work there. This in turn constrains growth of enterprises in the capital region. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">It is in the interests of the country as a whole that areas outside London, and the core city regions in particular, are given the ability to manage </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">their own ec</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">onomic destinies, in order</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> that as in most of continental Europe and the US, cities’ growth outstrips the national average.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">Core Cities and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">their LEPs, particularly where these are evolving into Combined Authorities, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">provide strong groupings </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">of functional </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">markets</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">, yet remain at a geographic level that achieves popular recognition. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">These are therefore the essential building blocks of fiscal devolution. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">However, the legislative process required to establish such a grouping is complex, and depends on</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> the grouping having contiguous boundaries, even though the travel-to-work area may include non-contiguous local authorities. It would be useful to remove bureaucratic restrictions to enable combined authorities to evolve on the basis of economic market re</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">lationships</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">, as the Government committed to do in its response to Lord Heseltine’s report “</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">No Stone Unturned”</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">The case for decentralisation has been accepted in principle by successive Governments. In practice, none has delivered in the face of resistance</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> from Whitehall Departments, particularly HM Treasury. Most recently Lord Heseltine’s Report “</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">No Stone Unturned</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">” recommended the creation of a single pot f</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">or LEPs of around £50 billion, </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">bringing together local economic development budgets from across White</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">hall. The Spending Round in June 2013 made clear that Whitehall had again fought successfully to resist this challenge, with the Local Growth Fund put at £2billion per annum and contributions from Departments hedged around with constraints on local freedom</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> to use the money</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">Furthermore, the Local Audit &amp; Accountability Bill threatens to undermine the ability of local areas to raise their own resources </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">to invest in growth, By bringing levies with the scope of the calculation of “excessive” council tax </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">rises and thus requiring annual referenda, this effectively destroys the agreement in the Leeds City Deal to establish a Transport Infrastructure Fund across the city region, with the potential to address the infrastructure constraints highlighted in parag</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">raph 6.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">In the light of these historic and current failures to deliver decentralisation and w</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">ith the prospect of further devolution to all the nations in the United Kingdom, except to England and its cities and counties, the time is now right for there to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">be an equivalent of the Calman </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">(Scotland) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">and Silk </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">(Wales) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">commissions for local government i</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">n England </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">to look at how fiscal </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">devolution might </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> be achieved in practice.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> This is particularly important as we recognise that having an internationally-competitiv</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">e tax regime is </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">fundamental to the nation’s economic prosperity and that increasing local fr</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">eedom to raise </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">taxation cannot be taken forward without an holistic review of the balance of central and local taxes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Codif</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">y the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> central-local gover</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">nment relationship –</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> This codification should be informed by the findings of  an independent </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> Commission, similar to that of the Calman Review in Scotland (or the Silk Review in Wales) </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">- covering all statutory responsibilities, complex funding formula (in</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">cluding Barnett), the balance of national and local taxation and constitutional relationship with Whitehall.</span></li></ul><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.5pt; padding-left:2.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">In the interim, some small measures to increase local freedom would be helpful –</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> this would reverse the</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> provisions in the Local Audit &amp;</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> Accountability Bill in relation to levies from any levy introduced by a Combined Authority in support of local growth</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">allow</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> local authorities to retain a larger percentage of business rate</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> growth</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt">which</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt"> would increase the local incentive to grow. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>